# 67_welcome_pen_path — OPENS the welcome-demo theatre arc (s288 m2).
#
# m1 (Canvas::animate_handle) proved the timeout→write→redraw loop works
# for editing an existing handle. m2 takes a different shape: THEATRE.
# The audience sees what looks like the Pen tool building a path, but
# nothing real is touched until the very end. The performance is staged
# entirely on a phantom overlay layer that the WelcomeAnimator owns;
# at the final tick, ONE real Path SceneNode is committed.
#
# ── Shape ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The script:
#   1. Asserts the new verb is in the `app` Scriptable's verb list.
#   2. Calls `app enact_pen_path "<d>" 1.0` — kicks off a Pen-path
#      performance over a hand-coded 5-anchor closed shape centred on
#      the test page.
#   3. Script ends.
#
# After the script returns, the WelcomeAnimator's Glib::Timeout runs the
# performance on the main loop. Scott watches the canvas for ~2 seconds
# as anchors appear (scale-in), out-handles extend, segments grow
# between them, the path closes, and at the end a real Path SceneNode
# materialises in the active layer (outline-only — no fill or stroke
# yet; that's Phase-2 work for a future milestone).
#
# ── No teardown ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Like the m1 smoke, this one does NOT tear down the layer. The
# animation lives past the script's natural end. Scott manually cleans
# up by closing the test layer or doc.
#
# ── Three-channel acceptance ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: script runs to completion without errors. The verb
#   surface check passes; the enact_pen_path call dispatches "ok".
#
# Visual channel (THE load-bearing channel for m2): Scott sees a
#   sequence of phantom anchor squares appear on the canvas, each
#   with its handle extending outward from the anchor, with a Bezier
#   segment growing from the previous anchor to it. The motion is
#   smooth, not stuttery. At the end of the performance, the phantoms
#   clear and a real outlined path is left on the canvas in their
#   place. The shape resembles the d-string's intended geometry: a
#   5-anchor closed curve roughly centred on the page.
#
# Build channel: Scott's compile.
#
# ── Hand-coded test geometry ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A simple 5-anchor closed curvy shape in user-space (Y-up, bottom-
# left origin). Centred near (500, 500) on a 1000×1000 page, with
# anchors arranged in a star-like configuration so the path-closing
# segment is unambiguously visible. Each anchor has out-handles
# pointing outward to make the lever lines obvious.
#
# Anchor 0: (500, 700) — top, handle out to (600, 700)
# Anchor 1: (700, 550) — upper right, handle out to (700, 450)
# Anchor 2: (600, 350) — lower right, handle out to (500, 350)
# Anchor 3: (400, 350) — lower left, handle out to (300, 450)
# Anchor 4: (300, 550) — upper left, handle out to (400, 700)
# Close → back to anchor 0
#
# d-string composed by hand from these anchors with cubic Bezier
# segments. Each C command has 3 coords: control-1 (out-handle of
# previous), control-2 (in-handle of current), endpoint (anchor).
# Z closes the path.

#[sub] === Phase 1: Verb surface check ===
#[sub] List registered Scriptables — `app` should appear in the list.
#[sub] The trace shows the verb list per Scriptable; visual inspection
#[sub] confirms enact_pen_path is present under `app`.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: Kick off the performance ===
#[sub] Single d-string arg + speed multiplier. Returns immediately;
#[sub] the animation runs asynchronously on the GTK main loop via
#[sub] Glib::Timeout. Script ends after this line — Scott watches
#[sub] the canvas for the next ~2 seconds.

app enact_pen_path "M 500 700 C 600 700 700 650 700 550 C 700 450 650 400 600 350 C 500 350 400 350 400 350 C 300 450 300 450 300 550 C 400 700 400 700 500 700 Z" 1.0

#[sub] === Script-end ===
#[sub] Animation continues on the main loop. Phantoms appear, then
#[sub] resolve to a real Path SceneNode at the end of the performance.
